{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540179"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.03,0.04,0.01,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66719"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9434"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52172"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2188"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4068"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11123"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66719"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the gynaecology clinic with her parent with a six-month history of cyclic lower abdominal pain. She has never had a menstrual period. She reports normal breast development starting at age 11. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her height and weight are at the 50th percentile for age. She has Tanner stage 4 breast development and normal axillary and pubic hair. External genital examination reveals a bluish bulging membrane at the vaginal introitus. Investigations reveal follicle stimulating hormone 5 IU/L (1-12), luteinizing hormone 7 IU/L (1-12), oestradiol 200 pmol/L (70-530), and normal karyotype 46,XX.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical hymenotomy","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone analogue","Magnetic resonance imaging pelvis","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Expectant management"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with primary amenorrhea and cyclic abdominal pain. The presence of normal secondary sexual characteristics, normal hormonal profile, and examination findings of a bluish bulging hymenal membrane are diagnostic of imperforate hymen with haematocolpos (accumulated menstrual blood in the vagina).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical hymenotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment for imperforate hymen. The procedure involves making a cruciate incision in the hymenal membrane to allow drainage of the accumulated blood. This should be performed by a gynaecologist experienced in paediatric and adolescent procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the anatomical obstruction and could potentially worsen the haematocolpos by inducing further menstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary when the diagnosis is clear on examination. It might be considered if there was uncertainty about the diagnosis or suspicion of other m\u00fcllerian anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone analogue\u003C/strong\u003E therapy would be inappropriate as this is not a hormonal problem. These medications are used in conditions like central precocious puberty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the condition will not resolve spontaneously and delay could lead to complications such as endometriosis or infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognition of the classic presentation: primary amenorrhea with cyclic pain in an adolescent with normal secondary sexual characteristics. The bluish bulging hymenal membrane on examination is pathognomonic. Early recognition and referral for surgical management prevents complications and relieves symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Imperforate hymen is a common cause of primary amenorrhea presenting with cyclic abdominal pain and examination findings of a bulging bluish hymenal membrane.","Surgical management with hymenotomy is the definitive treatment for imperforate hymen.","Normal secondary sexual characteristics and normal hormonal profile help distinguish imperforate hymen from other causes of primary amenorrhea."],"references":["Conway GS. Primary Amenorrhoea [Internet]. O\u0026G Magazine. 2017 [cited 2024 Dec 1];19(3). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/3-19/primary-amenorrhoea/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52172"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52172"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:22:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:23:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"dat